## 🧪 Testing and Verification

### 1. Alignment Verification
- Run `npm run test:unit` to execute [tests/schedule-alignment.test.js](file:///Users/brett/.gemini/antigravity/worktrees/couleeregiontennis.github.io/fix-2026-ics-generation/tests/schedule-alignment.test.js).
- This suite checks matching data across JSON schedules, weekly scoresheets, individual ICS files, and the master team ICS files to prevent double-booking or discrepancies.

### 2. GitHub CI/CD Actions
- A CI workflow in `.github/workflows/ci.yml` runs the unit tests on all push and pull requests targeting the `main` branch.

---

## 🌐 Cache Busting & Asset Updates

### 1. Version Queries
- Always append or increment the query parameter version string (e.g., `?v=2026.5` -> `?v=2026.6`) on references to modified static CSS and JS files in HTML files when deploying layout or script changes (e.g., in [index.html](file:///H:/Repo/couleeregiontennis.github.io/index.html), [pages/team.html](file:///H:/Repo/couleeregiontennis.github.io/pages/team.html), etc.).
- This forces browsers to fetch the newly modified files immediately rather than serving broken, stale cached layouts to users.

---

## 💻 Sandboxed Environment Tips

1. **Git Worktree Path Issue**: Running git commands inside standard sandbox mode can fail because `.git` points back to the parent repository. Always set `BypassSandbox: true` for git operations in this worktree.
2. **EPERM sandbox restriction on npm**: The standard sandbox blocks reading global npm directories (like fnm versions), causing `npm run` commands to fail. Execute test scripts directly using `node` (e.g. `node --test ...`) or set `BypassSandbox: true` to use npm.
